Accordingly an attempt has been made in the illustrative notes, on the pages with the text, to give sufficient prominence to the historical and literary features of the essay, and to show by numerous quotations what ancient and modern authors have uttered like thoughts, couched in similar forms of expression. ln numerous cases it will be seen that there is some- thing more than amere similarity of thought and expression. Without doubt many modern writers have drawn their inspiration direct from the lofty sentimenta of Cicero's essay, and thus the student is introduced to avery interesting and important literary. study oi the great master of Latin prose. If this portion of the work shall prove suggestive and stimulating, it will accomplish its intended purpose. ¹
